This is a subsection
====================

   As the header says. Note that you need to use the `p' command to
start the body of the section, after the `sect1' command.  Here's a
subsubsection:


 @{" This is a subsubsection " Link "This is a subsubsection"} 


@EndNode

@Node "This is a subsubsection" "example.guide/This is a subsubsection"
@Toc "This is a subsection"

This is a subsubsection
-----------------------

   Right. 5 levels of sections are available. Use the commands `sect',
`sect1', `sect2', `sect3', and `sect4' to get them.  This document uses
the `article' document style, which is appropriate for HOWTOs and other
docs; the `report' style (which includes the `chapt' sectioning
command) should be used for the LDP docs.


@EndNode

@Node "Example text" "example.guide/Example text"
@Next "Cross references"
@Prev "This is a subsection"
@Toc "Some examples"

Example text
============

   All right, so you're typing along, and you want to show some example
code, or example I/O with a program, whatever. Use the `code' or `verb'
"environments" for this, wrapped in a `tscreen' environment, as so:
     This is an example verb environment.

   As well as:
          This is an example code environment.

   The `tscreen' environment just sets the font to small type and
indents it nicely. It's not required for using `verb' or `code', but I
suggest that you do.

   The `Linuxdoc-SGML User's Guide' explains what special characters you
can and can't use in the `verb' and `code' environments.


@EndNode

@Node "Cross references" "example.guide/Cross references"
@Next "Using fonts"
@Prev "Example text"
@Toc "Some examples"

Cross references
================

   What about cross-references? This section has been marked with the
`label' command; using `ref' will provide a cross reference, as in "See
Section @{"Cross references" Link "Cross references"} " for more.

   Right now cross-references don't work in the `groff' translation for
plain ASCII.


@EndNode

@Node "Using fonts" "example.guide/Using fonts"
@Next "Lists"
@Prev "Cross references"
@Toc "Some examples"

Using fonts
===========

   You want fonts, we got fonts. Of course these won't show up in the
plain ASCII text, but they all map into the various output formats:
`boldface', `emphasis', sans serif, `slanted', `typewriter', and
`italics'.


@EndNode

@Node "Lists" "example.guide/Lists"
@Prev "Using fonts"
@Toc "Some examples"

Lists
=====

   Lists are easy as well. Just use the `itemize' element with the
`item' commands, seen here:
   @{b}*@{ub}  This is a list.

   @{b}*@{ub}  Nothing exciting about that.
        @{b}*@{ub}  Multiple levels are supported as well.

        @{b}*@{ub}  Again, that's no surprise.

       1.  Enumerated lists using `enum' also work.

       2.  Description environments using `descrip' along with `tag'
          are also available, as seen here.

    `First item.'
          Here's one item.

    `Second item.'
          Here's another.

    `Third item.'
          Can we go for three?

   @{b}*@{ub}  A final item to top it all off.

   This is just about everything that you need to get started with
writing SGML docs using the `linuxdoc-sgml' DTD. Please let me know if
you think something should be changed or added to this document.

@EndNode

